    {
      "id": "sec-editorial",
      "title": "Editor's Note",
      "layout": "single",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "id": "blk-editorial",
          "type": "html",
          "label": "Editor's Note",
          "data": {
            "label": "Editorial",
            "html": "<div style=\"padding:24px 28px;background:#fafafa;border-radius:12px;border:1px solid #efefef;position:relative;overflow:hidden\"><div style=\"position:absolute;top:14px;left:18px;font-size:64px;color:#f0f0f0;font-family:Georgia,serif;line-height:1;pointer-events:none;user-select:none\">“</div><div style=\"padding-left:36px\"><p style=\"font-family:Georgia,'Times New Roman',serif;font-size:15px;font-style:italic;color:#374151;line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 16px 0\">The question we are asked most often by residents is not <em>which</em> AI tool to use — it is how to know when to trust it. The answer has not changed from how we teach clinical reasoning: understand the prior probability, know the model’s failure modes, and always maintain the cognitive independence to disagree. AI is a second opinion, not a verdict.</p><div style=\"display:flex;align-items:center;gap:12px;padding-top:14px;border-top:1px solid #e5e7eb\"><div style=\"width:40px;height:40px;border-radius:50%;background:linear-gradient(135deg,#4F7FFF,#7C3AED);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;color:white;font-weight:800;font-family:Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;flex-shrink:0\">YE</div><div><div style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a2e;margin-bottom:2px\">Dr. Yasir El-Sherif, MD PhD</div><div style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;font-size:11px;color:#9ca3af\">Editor-in-Chief · Neurology AI Pulse</div></div></div></div></div>"
          }
        }
